    <h1>Complete BMI Guide – Body Mass Index Explained</h1>
<p>Body Mass Index (BMI) is a simple measurement used to determine whether your weight is healthy for your height. It is one of the most widely used health screening tools by doctors and healthcare professionals around the world.</p>

<p>BMI helps identify whether a person is underweight, at a healthy weight, overweight, or obese. While it does not directly measure body fat, it provides a useful starting point for understanding overall health.</p>

<h2>What is BMI?</h2>

<p>BMI stands for <strong>Body Mass Index</strong>. It is calculated using your height and weight and is commonly used to assess whether your body weight falls within a healthy range.</p>

<h2>How is BMI Calculated?</h2>

<p>The standard BMI formula is:</p>

<pre>BMI = Weight (kg) ÷ Height² (m²)</pre>

<p>For example, if a person weighs 70 kg and is 1.75 meters tall:</p>

<pre>BMI = 70 ÷ (1.75 × 1.75) = 22.86</pre>

<p>A BMI of 22.86 is considered within the healthy weight range.</p>
<h2>BMI Categories</h2>

<p>
The World Health Organization (WHO) classifies BMI into different categories that help determine whether a person's weight is considered healthy.
</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Below 18.5:</strong> Underweight</li>
<li><strong>18.5 – 24.9:</strong> Healthy Weight</li>
<li><strong>25.0 – 29.9:</strong> Overweight</li>
<li><strong>30.0 – 34.9:</strong> Obesity Class I</li>
<li><strong>35.0 – 39.9:</strong> Obesity Class II</li>
<li><strong>40.0 and above:</strong> Obesity Class III</li>
</ul>

<h2>Healthy BMI Range</h2>

<p>
For most adults, a BMI between <strong>18.5 and 24.9</strong> is considered healthy. Staying within this range may lower the risk of heart disease, high blood pressure, type 2 diabetes, and other weight-related health problems.
</p>

<h2>Who Should Use BMI?</h2>

<p>
BMI is designed for adults aged 18 years and older. It is a useful screening tool for both men and women. However, BMI may not accurately reflect body fat in athletes, pregnant women, older adults, or people with high muscle mass.
</p>
<h2>Understanding Underweight</h2>

<p>
A BMI below 18.5 is considered underweight. People who are underweight may not be getting enough nutrients or calories to maintain good health. Being underweight can increase the risk of weakened immunity, nutrient deficiencies, osteoporosis, and other health problems.
</p>

<p>
Common causes include poor nutrition, certain medical conditions, eating disorders, stress, or a naturally fast metabolism. If you are underweight, consult a healthcare professional to identify the underlying cause and create a healthy weight gain plan.
</p>

<h2>Understanding Overweight</h2>

<p>
A BMI between 25.0 and 29.9 is classified as overweight. Carrying extra body weight may increase the risk of developing chronic diseases such as high blood pressure, type 2 diabetes, heart disease, sleep apnea, and joint problems.
</p>

<p>
Healthy eating habits, regular physical activity, and gradual lifestyle changes can help reduce excess weight and improve overall health.
</p>

<h2>Understanding Obesity</h2>

<p>
A BMI of 30 or higher falls into the obesity category. Obesity is associated with a higher risk of serious health conditions, including cardiovascular disease, stroke, fatty liver disease, certain cancers, and metabolic disorders.
</p>


